#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:2
msgid "CMP0219"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:6
msgid ":command:`macro` invocations preserve backslashes in arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:8
msgid ""
"In CMake 4.3 and below, macro argument references (``${ARGN}``, ``${ARGV}``, "
"``${ARGV<n>}``, and named macro arguments) are substituted textually and "
"then evaluated by the called command. Backslashes in substituted values are "
"re-evaluated as escape prefixes, and invalid escape sequences (such as "
"``\\b`` in Windows paths) can cause errors. The same re-evaluation can also "
"occur for arguments passed to a :command:`variable_watch` callback command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:15
msgid ""
"CMake 4.4 and above prefer to preserve literal backslashes in those macro "
"argument references."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:18
msgid ""
"The ``OLD`` behavior for this policy is to interpret escape sequences in "
"macro argument references and in arguments passed to ``variable_watch()`` "
"callback commands. The ``NEW`` behavior is to preserve backslashes in those "
"values before command invocation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:23
msgid ""
"This policy applies to macro argument references and to arguments passed to "
"``variable_watch()`` callback commands. Other variable references keep their "
"existing behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:28
msgid "Mixed Policy Chains"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:30
msgid ""
"Whether pre-escaping occurs is determined by the policy setting at each call "
"site. When a project and its dependencies use different ``CMP0219`` "
"settings, each macro call in the chain follows the policy where that call "
"appears."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:35
msgid ""
"Consider a project (``CMP0219`` is ``OLD``) that calls a macro from "
"dependency A (upgraded to :command:`cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 4.4) "
"<cmake_minimum_required>`, so ``CMP0219`` is ``NEW``), which in turn "
"forwards arguments to a macro from dependency B (not yet upgraded, so "
"``CMP0219`` is ``OLD``):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:41
msgid ""
"# Dependency B: cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.24)\n"
"# CMP0219 is OLD inside dependency B.\n"
"macro(depB_store var_name)\n"
"  set(${var_name} \"${ARGN}\")\n"
"endmacro()\n"
"\n"
"# Dependency A: cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 4.4)\n"
"# CMP0219 is NEW inside dependency A.\n"
"macro(depA_forward var_name)\n"
"  depB_store(${var_name} ${ARGN})  # call site is NEW -> pre-escapes\n"
"endmacro()\n"
"\n"
"# Project: cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.24)\n"
"# CMP0219 is OLD in the project.\n"
"macro(my_wrapper var_name)\n"
"  depA_forward(${var_name} ${ARGN})  # call site is OLD -> no pre-escaping\n"
"endmacro()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:61
msgid ""
"In a fully ``OLD`` chain, each macro boundary re-evaluates backslash "
"escapes, so callers must add extra escaping layers to compensate. To pass "
"the Windows path ``C:\\build\\new\\temp`` through three ``OLD`` boundaries, "
"the caller needs eight backslashes per separator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:66
msgid ""
"my_wrapper(result \"C:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\build\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\new\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"
"\\temp\")\n"
"message(\"${result}\")  # -> C:\\build\\new\\temp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:71
msgid ""
"When dependency A upgrades and the middle boundary becomes ``NEW``, that "
"boundary preserves backslashes instead of consuming a level. The same input "
"now retains an extra layer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:75
msgid ""
"# Same 8x-escaped input through OLD -> NEW -> OLD:\n"
"my_wrapper(result \"C:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\build\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\new\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"
"\\temp\")\n"
"message(\"${result}\")  # -> C:\\\\build\\\\new\\\\temp  (one extra layer)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:81
msgid "The caller must then use half the escaping to reach the native path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:83
msgid ""
"# Only 4x-escaped input needed for OLD -> NEW -> OLD:\n"
"my_wrapper(result \"C:\\\\\\\\build\\\\\\\\new\\\\\\\\temp\")\n"
"message(\"${result}\")  # -> C:\\build\\new\\temp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:89
msgid ""
"When a dependency updates its :command:`cmake_minimum_required` version to "
"4.4 or above, call sites inside that dependency begin pre-escaping. Callers "
"that previously added extra backslash layers to compensate for multiple "
"levels of ``OLD`` re-evaluation may then need fewer escape layers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/CMP0219.rst:95
msgid ""
"Where possible, converting paths to forward slashes with :command:"
"`cmake_path(CONVERT ... TO_CMAKE_PATH_LIST)` avoids the issue entirely, "
"because forward slashes require no escaping regardless of the policy setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/include/STANDARD_ADVICE.rst:1
msgid ""
"This policy was introduced in CMake version |INTRODUCED_IN_CMAKE_VERSION|. "
"It may be set by :command:`cmake_policy` or :command:"
"`cmake_minimum_required`. If it is not set, CMake |WARNS_OR_DOES_NOT_WARN|, "
"and uses ``OLD`` behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../policy/include/DEPRECATED.rst:2
msgid ""
"The ``OLD`` behavior of a policy is :ref:`deprecated by definition <cmake-"
"policies-intro>` and may be removed in a future version of CMake."
msgstr ""
